      letter: 'C',
      shortDef: 'Net operating income divided by property value, expressing the annual return a property generates independent of financing.',
      fullDef: 'The capitalization rate (cap rate) is calculated by dividing a property\'s net operating income (NOI) by its current market value or purchase price. It represents the annual return an all-cash buyer would earn from the property\'s operations, excluding financing effects.\n\nCap rates vary significantly by market and property type. In expensive gateway markets, cap rates for multifamily properties may be 3–4%; in Midwest or Sun Belt secondary markets, 6–8% is common. A lower cap rate signals higher prices relative to income; a higher cap rate means more income relative to price, often with more risk.\n\nCap rate is most useful for comparing similar properties in the same market. It does not account for leverage, appreciation, or capital expenditures. Sophisticated investors use it alongside cash-on-cash return, IRR, and gross rent multiplier for a more complete picture.',
      example: 'A rental property with $24,000 in annual NOI purchased for $320,000 has a cap rate of 7.5%—higher than the 5% cap rate on a comparable property in a pricier neighborhood.',
      related: ['cash-on-cash-return', 'noi', 'gross-rent-multiplier', '1031-exchange'],
