      letter: 'C',
      shortDef: 'Annual pre-tax cash flow divided by total cash invested, measuring the actual cash yield on the money you put into a leveraged investment.',
      fullDef: 'Cash-on-cash return measures the actual cash yield relative to the cash you personally invested (down payment plus closing costs plus initial repairs). Unlike cap rate, it accounts for mortgage financing. The formula is: annual pre-tax cash flow / total cash invested.\n\nThis metric is critical for leveraged investors because financing amplifies returns (positive leverage) or destroys them (negative leverage). A property with a 5% cap rate can produce a 10–12% cash-on-cash return if financed at a lower interest rate than the cap rate; conversely, rising interest rates can flip a formerly profitable property cash-flow negative.\n\nCash-on-cash return does not capture appreciation or principal paydown—two other major components of real estate returns. Used alongside total return calculations, it tells investors how much actual cash they are receiving on their invested capital each year.',
      example: 'After a $60,000 down payment and $10,000 in closing costs, the rental produced $5,600 in annual cash flow—an 8% cash-on-cash return on the $70,000 invested.',
