      fullDef: 'Net operating income (NOI) equals total revenue (rents, laundry income, parking, late fees) minus operating expenses (property taxes, insurance, management fees, maintenance, vacancy allowance). Mortgage payments, depreciation, and income taxes are excluded—NOI represents the property\'s standalone earning power before financing.\n\nNOI is used to calculate cap rate and DSCR, and it drives property valuation in commercial real estate. Increasing NOI—through rent increases, expense reduction, or adding revenue streams—directly increases property value (Value = NOI / Cap Rate).\n\nA common mistake is underestimating operating expenses and overstating NOI. Rules of thumb: vacancy at 5–10%, maintenance at 5–10% of gross rents, management at 8–12%, and CapEx reserves at 5–10%. Optimistic NOI projections lead to overpaying for properties.',
      example: 'The duplex generated $36,000 in annual rent; after $14,400 in operating expenses (taxes, insurance, maintenance, vacancy), the NOI was $21,600.',
