      fullDef: 'A 1031 exchange allows investors to sell an investment property and defer capital gains taxes by reinvesting the full proceeds into a like-kind replacement property. The exchange must follow strict rules: the investor cannot touch the sale proceeds (held by a qualified intermediary), the replacement property must be identified within 45 days of the sale, and closing must occur within 180 days.\n\nThe like-kind requirement is broadly interpreted for real estate—any US investment property qualifies as like-kind to any other US investment property. Primary residences, stocks, and foreign property do not qualify.\n\nOver time, serial 1031 exchanges allow investors to continuously defer taxes and build a much larger portfolio. Upon death, heirs receive a stepped-up cost basis, effectively eliminating accumulated deferred gains. This is one of the most powerful tax advantages available to real estate investors.',
      example: 'By 1031 exchanging her $400,000 duplex (purchased for $180,000) into a $600,000 six-unit building, the investor deferred $44,000 in capital gains tax and acquired a larger income-producing asset.',
      related: ['cap-rate', 'cash-on-cash-return', 'leverage', 'real-estate-depreciation'],
