      fullDef: 'House hacking is a strategy where an owner-occupant purchases a 2–4 unit property, lives in one unit, and rents out the remaining units. The rental income offsets—and in many markets covers entirely—the mortgage payment, effectively allowing the owner to live for free or nearly free while building equity.\n\nThe financial benefits are significant: owner-occupied financing (FHA loans allow 3.5% down on 2–4 unit properties) is far cheaper than investor financing (typically 20–25% down). Living in the property also qualifies the purchase for capital gains exclusion on the owner-occupied portion when sold.\n\nHouse hacking requires willingness to manage tenants next door—a trade-off some find uncomfortable. For investors willing to accept this, it is one of the most powerful wealth-building tools available to people without large capital reserves.',
