      fullDef: 'The BRRRR method aims to recycle capital rather than tying it up in each property. The investor buys a distressed property below market value, rehabilitates it to increase value and rental appeal, rents it to a tenant, then performs a cash-out refinance based on the improved appraised value, pulling out most or all of the original cash invested. The extracted capital funds the next acquisition.\n\nThe key is "forced appreciation" created by the rehab—buying below market and improving the property increases its appraised value, enabling a refinance that recovers the down payment and renovation costs. If executed properly, the investor ends up with a stabilized rental with minimal cash left in the deal.\n\nRisks include renovation cost overruns, appraisal shortfalls, difficulty securing tenants at projected rents, and refinance terms that do not allow adequate debt service. Experienced investors build in conservative assumptions and deep renovation expertise to mitigate these risks.',
