      fullDef: 'Loan-to-value ratio (LTV) is calculated by dividing the mortgage balance by the property\'s appraised value. A $240,000 loan on a $300,000 property is an 80% LTV. LTV is the primary risk measure for mortgage lenders—lower LTV means more borrower equity protecting the lender against loss.\n\nLTV affects loan availability, interest rate, and whether PMI is required. Conventional loans above 80% LTV require PMI; FHA loans require mortgage insurance regardless of LTV. Investment property loans typically cap at 75–80% LTV with the best terms at 70–75% LTV.\n\nFor investors, LTV management balances amplification of returns (higher LTV) against risk and debt service. Maintaining adequate equity (lower LTV) provides a buffer against value declines and easier refinancing options.',
